article.description: Ukari Figgs scored 16 points as the Portland Fire handed the Washington Mystics their season-high fifth straight loss, 67-65 Friday night.
article.headline: Fire keep pace in West battle, Mystics fall
article.linkText: Fire's win over Mystics has Liberty atop East
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ukari Figgs scored 16 points as the Portland
Fire handed the Washington Mystics their season-high fifth straight
loss, 67-65 Friday night.

	   The Mystics fell a game behind the New York Liberty, who beat
the Miami Sol on Friday, in the Eastern Conference.

	   "I feel that we broke out of our rut to a great degree, we just
did not win the game,'' Washington coach Marianne Stanley said.
"We have to appreciate the fact that we played together as a team,
we played hard, and we could have easily been saying: 'Hey, great
win. We're out of the rut.' ''

	   The Fire (16-13), fighting for the final playoff spot in the
Western Conference, snapped a three-game road losing streak.

	   "If we just keep coming out and playing hard and playing
together, we can beat anybody in this league,'' Figgs said. "This
was a huge win for us.''

	   Chamique Holdsclaw led the Mystics (15-11) with 26 points and
nine rebounds. Annie Burgess added 11 points and Muriel Page had a
season-high six assists.

	   Holdsclaw left the game with 2:02 remaining after twisting her
right ankle and is listed as day-to-day. Holdsclaw recently missed
nine games with a sprained left ankle.

	   Sylvia Crawley scored 11 points for Portland and DeMya Walker
added 10. Alisa Burras finished with eight points and 11 rebounds,
including the crucial grab of teammate Walker's missed shot with
seven seconds left.

	   Tamicha Jackson missed two free throws with 3.1 seconds left but
knocked her own rebound out of bounds, leaving just 1.4 seconds for
the Mystics, who failed to get a final shot in losing their fourth
straight at home.

	   The Mystics missed five free throws in the final four minutes
and made 10 of 17 for the game.

	   Holdsclaw scored 11 straight points for Washington and the
Mystics pulled to 65-63 on her steal and layup with 3:30 remaining.
They tied it at 65 on Miller's three-point play with 2:02 left.

	   "We did an excellent job of playing together and keeping our
composure when they made that comeback in the second half,'' Figgs
said. "People aren't giving us credit for what we're doing game in
and game out, all season long. But that's OK as long as we know
what we can do.''

	   Figgs scored eight points, including a pair of 3-pointers, to
spark the Fire on an 18-7 run midway through the second half,
capped by Crawley's layup for a 61-50 lead with 9:18 left.

	   "Being the two-guard, you've got to come out and knock down
some shots,'' Figgs said. "Tonight, I was just glad that I was
able to give the team a little bit of a lift, and that was getting
our post players open off the pick-and-roll.''

	   The Mystics led by as many as seven points in a first half that
featured six lead changes and two ties.
